>Nigel: ?ADEMOO H3 AMOOvED +74 74
>Jesse: ABGILNP I3 BAP +25 25
#note saw GALOPIN, passed it up. want to bingo back as fast as possible. what's amazing is that Q thinks that BAP at 3G keeping the A is 77% to bingo next turn versus 52% with my placement - didn't occur to me that sacrificing 12 points to keep the A would be well worth it! the other factors that contribute to the sim are that I can still bingo from the M and that the double-double stays open.
>Nigel: EEGHIOO G3 GOO +24 98
>Jesse: EGILNUV F5 LUV +14 39
#note I would've bingoed with any 2 out of 3 of the tiles I drew after BAP 3G, illustrating the strength of that leave. maybe just fish BAPU at I6 and go after INVEIGLE/ENVEIGLE/INVEAGLE, although I'm worried about Nigel blocking. close on a sim.
>Nigel: AEEEHIS G8 EE +9 107
>Jesse: BEGIINT 5E B....ING +52 91
>Nigel: AEHIKRS F9 SHAKIER +78 185
>Jesse: DEINTWY 15D WI.EY +45 136
#note Original: Nigel said 'hold' very quietly after Jesse played WIREY; Jesse did not hear. Nigel spun the board, and said 'hold,' again, very quietly. Jesse didn't hear, and drew replacement tiles. At that point, Nigel spoke up more audibly, and the players called the director. After asking both annotators (one of whom says she might have heard the second 'hold' but wasn't sure) and a review of the video, the director call was that Jesse could not have heard the 'hold' call and play should continue without a challenge.     Jesse: Actually I think Nigel only said hold twice. I didn't hear him the first time, and the second time I already had tiles out on the table. I felt terrible about what happened. Against most players I wouldn't give them the benefit of the doubt, but I realized after this game Nigel was pretty much inaudible on the score on many turns. I know him deeply as a competitor and should've trusted him, and I regret not telling the director to let the challenge be allowed.
